Body:

In which I hope to offer a useful model for considering the ways in which we humans communicate and take action. 

But first, some acknowledgments. 

## Sources 

I first came across these patterns when reading Ken Wilber's book *A Brief History of Everything*, back in 1997 or so. Wilber describes these as levels of development. 

But Wilber references the work of Beck and Cowan, which built on earlier work by Clare Graves, and so I then read the *Spiral Dynamics* book, from 1996. 

And then I somehow stumbled across a more recent book by Hanzi Freinacht, in which he refers back to the work by Graves, Beck and Cowan as the "awkward uncle" of some of his work, and acknowledges that this model of "Value Memes," or "vMemes" (as they are called by Beck and Cowan) "catches something vital," and that, once you see them, "it's certainly hard to look away." 

This has been true for me as well. And so this model, in one form or another, has continued to fascinate me over the years: it just seems to make so much sense, and to explain so much.

So I've given it a lot of thought to this over the last quarter century. 

And here is where I've ended up (or at least currently sit). 

## The Patterns

I've found it most useful to think of these various *developmental levels*, or *value memes*, as recurring patterns for human communication and action. I don't think that any of these patterns are inherently superior to any of the others, and I think it best to consider each pattern as having both advantages and disadvantages, and that it is best to call upon each of these as needed, and as they best fit the current circumstances of an individual, organization or society. 

I want to present these first in the form of a table, to make it easy to see them as a collection, before drilling down into individual patterns. 

These are the columns contained in the table. 

Seq
: The sequence numbers are assigned to imply a normal developmental sequence, and to create the usual order in which they are presented.

Title
: The title represents a very brief description of each pattern. 

Color
: Colors were originally assigned by Graves, Beck and Cowan (but then futzed with by Wilber and his group, over time). I'm just using the original Spiral Dynamics colors here. 

Self vs. Group 
: Beck and Cowan observed that these things tend to bounce back and forth between an asssertion of the importance of the self, and the importance of the collective. I've found this to be an important insight, and so am including it here. 

Description
: Some descriptive words and phrases that apply to each pattern.

